---
import Layout from '@/components/astro/Layout.astro';

const pageTitle = 'When Should Your Texas Business Hire a Lobbyist? The Timing Guide';
const pageDescription = 'Most businesses hire lobbyists six months too late, when costs triple and success rates plummet. Texas lobbyist Byron Campbell reveals the warning signals, cost analysis, and strategic windows that separate winners from wasted money.';

const schema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: pageTitle,
  description: pageDescription,
  author: {
    '@type': 'Person',
    name: 'Byron Campbell'
  },
  datePublished: '2025-01-09',
  dateModified: '2025-01-09'
};
---

<Layout title={pageTitle} description={pageDescription} schema={schema}>
  <!-- Hero Section -->
  <section class="bg-gradient-to-b from-texas-blue-50 via-white to-background py-20 lg:py-28 border-b border-border">
    <div class="container max-w-4xl">
      <div class="mb-8">
        <a
          href="/guides"
          class="inline-flex items-center text-sm font-medium text-texas-blue-600 hover:text-texas-blue-700 transition-colors group"
        >
          <svg class="w-4 h-4 mr-2 transition-transform group-hover:-translate-x-1" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M10 19l-7-7m0 0l7-7m-7 7h18" />
          </svg>
          Back to all guides
        </a>
      </div>

      <div class="inline-flex items-center rounded-full bg-texas-blue-500/10 px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-texas-blue-700 mb-6">
        Strategic Timing Guide
      </div>

      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl font-bold mb-6 leading-tight tracking-tight">
        When Should Your Texas Business Hire a Lobbyist?
      </h1>

      <p class="text-xl md:text-2xl text-muted-foreground mb-10 leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        I've watched businesses waste six figures hiring lobbyists too late. The pattern is predictable: they call in February about legislation filed in November, expecting miracles at triple the price.
      </p>

      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-6 text-sm text-muted-foreground border-t border-border pt-6">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-texas-blue-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M16 7a4 4 0 11-8 0 4 4 0 018 0zM12 14a7 7 0 00-7 7h14a7 7 0 00-7-7z" />
          </svg>
          <span class="font-medium">By Byron Campbell, Texas Lobbyist</span>
        </div>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-texas-blue-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 8v4l3 3m6-3a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z" />
          </svg>
          <span class="font-medium">18 min read</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Main Content -->
  <article class="py-16 lg:py-20">
    <div class="container max-w-3xl">

      <!-- Introduction -->
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none mb-12">
        <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed">
          Last March, a manufacturing company called me about legislation that would have effectively shut down two of their Texas facilities. The bill had been filed in November, gained momentum in January, and was now two weeks from a committee vote. They wanted to hire me to fix it.
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed">
          I told them the truth: six months earlier, we could have shaped this bill before it was filed. Three months earlier, we could have built a coalition to oppose it. Even two months earlier, we could have positioned amendments to gut the harmful provisions. But two weeks before the vote? We'd be paying premium rates for a low-probability save, burning through their budget on damage control instead of strategic positioning.
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed">
          Timing determines lobbying success more than money or connections. The businesses that win at the Capitol understand when to engage, what signals demand immediate action, and how the costs multiply when you wait too long. The ones that lose hire lobbyists when they're desperate—which is exactly when lobbying is most expensive and least effective.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- The 7 Warning Signals -->
      <section id="warning-signals" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
        <div class="bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-500 rounded-r-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">The 7 Warning Signals You Can't Ignore</h2>
          <p class="text-red-700 font-medium">When these appear, hire immediately or accept the consequences</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
          <p>
            Some situations don't require debate about whether you need a lobbyist. The only question is how fast you can get one under contract. If you see any of these signals, you're already behind.
          </p>

          <div class="not-prose my-8 space-y-4">
            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-red-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-10 h-10 bg-red-500 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-bold">1</div>
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Legislation Directly Threatens Your Business Model</h3>
                  <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-3">
                    A bill gets filed that would ban your product, require licensing you can't obtain, or impose compliance costs that make your business uneconomical. This is existential threat territory.
                  </p>
                  <div class="bg-red-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                    <p class="text-sm text-red-900 mb-1"><strong>Example:</strong> HB 2847 would require all food delivery services to maintain $5M insurance policies per driver and verify employment status for all contractors—effectively forcing you to convert 2,000 independent contractors to W-2 employees.</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-red-800 mt-2 mb-0"><strong>Cost of waiting:</strong> If you hire after the bill passes committee, you're fighting on the House floor with limited options. If you hire before filing, you might get the bill amended in draft stage or stopped before it gains momentum.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-orange-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-10 h-10 bg-orange-500 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-bold">2</div>
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Your Industry Faces Coordinated Regulatory Attack</h3>
                  <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-3">
                    Multiple bills filed by different legislators, backed by organized opposition groups, supported by negative media coverage. This isn't random—someone's running a campaign against your industry.
                  </p>
                  <div class="bg-orange-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                    <p class="text-sm text-orange-900 mb-1"><strong>What this looks like:</strong> Three bills filed in the first week targeting different aspects of your business, coordinated testimony from opposition groups at interim hearings, op-eds in major newspapers calling for regulation.</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-orange-800 mt-2 mb-0"><strong>What you need:</strong> A lobbyist who can coordinate defense across multiple committees, build counter-coalitions, and respond to opposition research before it becomes conventional wisdom at the Capitol.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-amber-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-10 h-10 bg-amber-500 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-bold">3</div>
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Competitors Have Lobbyists and You Don't</h3>
                  <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-3">
                    You discover your three largest competitors all have Austin representation. They're showing up at interim hearings, meeting with committee staff, positioning favorable legislation. You're not even on the Capitol's radar.
                  </p>
                  <div class="bg-amber-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                    <p class="text-sm text-amber-900 mb-1"><strong>The disadvantage compounds:</strong> Your competitors are building relationships during the interim, positioning their preferred policies, and identifying opportunities you don't even know exist. By the time session starts, they've already won because they shaped the agenda before you showed up.</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-amber-800 mt-2 mb-0"><strong>Strategic response:</strong> Hire during the interim to level the playing field. You can't match relationships built over years, but you can at least get in the room where decisions happen.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-yellow-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-10 h-10 bg-yellow-600 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-bold">4</div>
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Major Appropriations or Procurement Opportunities</h3>
                  <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-3">
                    The state is allocating budget for programs your business serves, or issuing RFPs worth millions. Without legislative relationships, you're competing at a disadvantage against vendors who've been positioning for months.
                  </p>
                  <div class="bg-yellow-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                    <p class="text-sm text-yellow-900 mb-1"><strong>Budget cycle reality:</strong> Legislative Budget Board staff start building next session's budget 18 months in advance. Agency priorities get set a year ahead. If you show up when the budget hits the House floor, the decisions are already made.</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-yellow-800 mt-2 mb-0"><strong>Optimal timing:</strong> Engage 12-18 months before the session to influence interim committee recommendations and LBB staff proposals.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-purple-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-10 h-10 bg-purple-500 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-bold">5</div>
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Complex Licensing or Permitting Battles</h3>
                  <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-3">
                    Your application is stuck at TCEQ, Railroad Commission, or another state agency. Staff won't return calls. Your issue involves multiple agencies with conflicting jurisdictions. Agency rulemaking threatens to impose requirements you can't meet.
                  </p>
                  <div class="bg-purple-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                    <p class="text-sm text-purple-900 mb-1"><strong>Why lobbying helps:</strong> Agencies answer to the Legislature. Your lobbyist has relationships with both agency leadership and the legislative committee that oversees them. That dual access creates leverage you don't have as an applicant.</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-purple-800 mt-2 mb-0"><strong>When to engage:</strong> As soon as you realize normal channels aren't working. Waiting months while your application languishes costs more than the lobbying fees.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-blue-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-10 h-10 bg-blue-500 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-bold">6</div>
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Your Trade Association Can't or Won't Help</h3>
                  <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-3">
                    The association's priorities don't align with yours, their lobbyist is stretched too thin to handle your specific issue, or internal politics prevent them from taking positions that help you.
                  </p>
                  <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                    <p class="text-sm text-blue-900 mb-1"><strong>Common scenario:</strong> Your association represents 200 members with competing interests. They can only take positions that serve the majority, which means your specific regulatory problem gets no attention. You need dedicated advocacy, not committee-negotiated compromises.</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-blue-800 mt-2 mb-0"><strong>Decision point:</strong> When you realize the association won't or can't advocate for your position, hire your own representation. Hoping they'll suddenly prioritize your issue is expensive wishful thinking.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-green-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-10 h-10 bg-green-500 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-bold">7</div>
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">You're Planning Major Texas Expansion</h3>
                  <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-3">
                    You're building new facilities, making significant capital investments, or entering Texas markets. Regulatory clarity and favorable policy environment directly affect your ROI on those investments.
                  </p>
                  <div class="bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                    <p class="text-sm text-green-900 mb-1"><strong>Strategic timing:</strong> Hire a lobbyist 12+ months before you announce expansion. They can help you understand the regulatory landscape, identify potential obstacles, and position favorable policies before you've committed capital.</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-green-800 mt-2 mb-0"><strong>Value proposition:</strong> Discovering that pending legislation will require $2M in facility modifications is valuable information <em>before</em> you buy the land, not after you break ground.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="not-prose bg-texas-blue-50 border-l-4 border-texas-blue-500 rounded-r-lg p-6 my-8">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-2">The Pattern to Watch</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-texas-blue-900 mb-0">
              Notice the theme: every signal involves threats or opportunities worth multiples of lobbying costs. A $100K lobbying investment to protect $5M in annual revenue is obvious math. A $75K investment to position for $10M in state contracts makes sense. The mistake is waiting until the threat is imminent or the opportunity is about to close. That's when costs triple and success rates plummet.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- The Cost of Waiting -->
      <section id="cost-of-waiting" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
        <div class="bg-amber-50 border-l-4 border-amber-500 rounded-r-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">The Real Cost of Waiting</h2>
          <p class="text-amber-700 font-medium">How timing multiplies expense and tanks success rates</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
          <p>
            Let me show you what the timing difference costs in actual dollars and probability of success. Same lobbyist, same issue, wildly different outcomes based solely on when you hire.
          </p>

          <div class="not-prose my-8">
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-border overflow-hidden">
              <div class="bg-gradient-to-r from-green-500 to-green-600 p-4">
                <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-0">Scenario: Healthcare regulation requiring $3M facility upgrade</h3>
              </div>

              <div class="p-6 space-y-6">
                <div class="border-l-4 border-green-500 pl-6">
                  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
                    <div class="flex-shrink-0 px-3 py-1 bg-green-500 text-white text-sm font-bold rounded">PROACTIVE</div>
                    <h4 class="font-bold text-lg mb-0">Hired 12 Months Before Session</h4>
                  </div>
                  <div class="bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-4 mb-3">
                    <p class="text-sm text-green-900 mb-2"><strong>What happens:</strong></p>
                    <ul class="text-sm text-green-800 ml-4 space-y-1">
                      <li>• Testify at interim hearings showing regulation's unintended costs</li>
                      <li>• Build relationships with committee staff before bill gets drafted</li>
                      <li>• Work with potential authors to include exemptions in original language</li>
                      <li>• Coordinate with trade associations for unified opposition</li>
                      <li>• Position economic impact study that legislators reference in debate</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
                    <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-green-200 p-4">
                      <div class="text-xs text-green-700 mb-1">Total Investment</div>
                      <div class="text-2xl font-bold text-green-700">$85K</div>
                      <div class="text-xs text-green-600 mt-1">18-month retainer + expenses</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-green-200 p-4">
                      <div class="text-xs text-green-700 mb-1">Success Probability</div>
                      <div class="text-2xl font-bold text-green-700">70%</div>
                      <div class="text-xs text-green-600 mt-1">Kill bill or get exemption</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-green-200 p-4">
                      <div class="text-xs text-green-700 mb-1">Expected Value</div>
                      <div class="text-2xl font-bold text-green-700">$2.1M</div>
                      <div class="text-xs text-green-600 mt-1">70% × $3M saved</div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                  <p class="text-xs text-green-700 mt-3 italic">ROI: 24x investment (saved $2.1M for $85K cost)</p>
                </div>

                <div class="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-6">
                  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
                    <div class="flex-shrink-0 px-3 py-1 bg-blue-500 text-white text-sm font-bold rounded">REACTIVE</div>
                    <h4 class="font-bold text-lg mb-0">Hired 2 Months Before Session</h4>
                  </div>
                  <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-4 mb-3">
                    <p class="text-sm text-blue-900 mb-2"><strong>What happens:</strong></p>
                    <ul class="text-sm text-blue-800 ml-4 space-y-1">
                      <li>• Bill language already drafted without your input</li>
                      <li>• Committee staff briefed by regulation supporters, not you</li>
                      <li>• Play defense trying to amend rather than shape original language</li>
                      <li>• Rushed economic study lacks credibility</li>
                      <li>• Coalition building happens mid-session under time pressure</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
                    <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-blue-200 p-4">
                      <div class="text-xs text-blue-700 mb-1">Total Investment</div>
                      <div class="text-2xl font-bold text-blue-700">$95K</div>
                      <div class="text-xs text-blue-600 mt-1">Higher session rate + rush fees</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-blue-200 p-4">
                      <div class="text-xs text-blue-700 mb-1">Success Probability</div>
                      <div class="text-2xl font-bold text-blue-700">35%</div>
                      <div class="text-xs text-blue-600 mt-1">Amended or killed</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-blue-200 p-4">
                      <div class="text-xs text-blue-700 mb-1">Expected Value</div>
                      <div class="text-2xl font-bold text-blue-700">$1.05M</div>
                      <div class="text-xs text-blue-600 mt-1">35% × $3M saved</div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                  <p class="text-xs text-blue-700 mt-3 italic">ROI: 11x investment (saved $1.05M for $95K cost, but lower probability)</p>
                </div>

                <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-6">
                  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
                    <div class="flex-shrink-0 px-3 py-1 bg-red-500 text-white text-sm font-bold rounded">CRISIS</div>
                    <h4 class="font-bold text-lg mb-0">Hired Mid-Session (Bill Already Through Committee)</h4>
                  </div>
                  <div class="bg-red-50 rounded-lg p-4 mb-3">
                    <p class="text-sm text-red-900 mb-2"><strong>What happens:</strong></p>
                    <ul class="text-sm text-red-800 ml-4 space-y-1">
                      <li>• Bill already has momentum and committee support</li>
                      <li>• Fighting on House floor with limited amendment opportunities</li>
                      <li>• Opposition coalition fully mobilized</li>
                      <li>• "Emergency" premium pricing for fire-drill work</li>
                      <li>• Most amendments get ruled non-germane or politically impossible</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
                    <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-red-200 p-4">
                      <div class="text-xs text-red-700 mb-1">Total Investment</div>
                      <div class="text-2xl font-bold text-red-700">$135K</div>
                      <div class="text-xs text-red-600 mt-1">Crisis pricing + expedited research</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-red-200 p-4">
                      <div class="text-xs text-red-700 mb-1">Success Probability</div>
                      <div class="text-2xl font-bold text-red-700">15%</div>
                      <div class="text-xs text-red-600 mt-1">Hail Mary territory</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-red-200 p-4">
                      <div class="text-xs text-red-700 mb-1">Expected Value</div>
                      <div class="text-2xl font-bold text-red-700">$450K</div>
                      <div class="text-xs text-red-600 mt-1">15% × $3M saved</div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                  <p class="text-xs text-red-700 mt-3 italic">ROI: 3x investment (still positive, but you're paying 59% more for 79% lower success rate)</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="not-prose my-8 space-y-6">
            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-amber-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-3">The Timing Cost Multipliers</h3>
              <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-4">
                Three factors drive costs up and success rates down when you hire late:
              </p>
              <div class="space-y-3">
                <div class="bg-amber-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                  <p class="font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">1. Premium Pricing for Fire-Drill Work</p>
                  <p class="text-sm text-amber-800 mb-0">Good lobbyists charge 30-50% more for crisis work that disrupts their existing client commitments and requires working around the clock during critical vote periods.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-amber-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                  <p class="font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">2. Strategic Options Already Foreclosed</p>
                  <p class="text-sm text-amber-800 mb-0">Early engagement means shaping bills in draft stage, building coalitions during the interim, positioning economic studies before hearings. Late engagement means playing defense with limited moves available.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-amber-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                  <p class="font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">3. The Best Lobbyists Are Fully Booked</p>
                  <p class="text-sm text-amber-800 mb-0">Top-tier lobbyists take clients 6-12 months before session. If you're hiring in January, you're choosing from whoever still has capacity—which often means less experienced advocates or those struggling to maintain a full client roster.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-red-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-3 text-red-900">The "Too Late" Scenarios</h3>
              <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-4">
                Some situations are genuinely too late for effective lobbying:
              </p>
              <div class="space-y-2 text-sm">
                <div class="bg-red-50 rounded p-3">
                  <p class="font-semibold text-red-900 mb-1">Bill has passed both chambers and is heading to Governor</p>
                  <p class="text-red-800 mb-0">Your only option is convincing the Governor to veto—possible if you have extraordinary relationships, but probability drops to single digits.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-red-50 rounded p-3">
                  <p class="font-semibold text-red-900 mb-1">Final week of session with complex bill in conference committee</p>
                  <p class="text-red-800 mb-0">Conference committees work behind closed doors with limited amendment opportunities. If you're not already positioned with conferees, you're watching from outside.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-red-50 rounded p-3">
                  <p class="font-semibold text-red-900 mb-1">Issue has become politically toxic or high-profile media story</p>
                  <p class="text-red-800 mb-0">Once your issue is on the front page with legislators taking public positions, the political dynamics become nearly impossible to reverse mid-session.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p class="text-sm text-red-800 mt-3 italic">If you find yourself in these scenarios, hire a lobbyist anyway—but for next session's positioning, not this session's save.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- The Four Hiring Windows -->
      <section id="hiring-windows" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
        <div class="bg-purple-50 border-l-4 border-purple-500 rounded-r-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">The Four Hiring Windows</h2>
          <p class="text-purple-700 font-medium">Strategic, proactive, reactive, and crisis—where you fit determines outcomes</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
          <p>
            Every lobbying engagement falls into one of four timing windows. The window you choose determines what's possible, what it costs, and who's available to help you.
          </p>

          <div class="not-prose my-8 space-y-6">
            <div class="bg-gradient-to-r from-green-50 to-white border-l-4 border-green-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-4 mb-4">
                <div class="flex-shrink-0">
                  <div class="w-16 h-16 bg-green-500 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-bold text-2xl">S</div>
                </div>
                <div class="flex-1">
