            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border-2 border-amber-500 p-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4 text-amber-900">Revenue-Based Decision Framework</h3>
              <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-4">
                Use these rough guidelines to assess whether lobbying fits your budget:
              </p>

              <div class="space-y-4">
                <div class="flex items-start gap-4 bg-red-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                  <div class="flex-shrink-0 text-2xl font-bold text-red-700">$0-2M</div>
                  <div class="flex-1">
                    <p class="font-semibold text-red-900 mb-1">Lobbying Rarely Makes Sense</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-red-800 mb-2">Unless you face existential regulatory threat, the $75-150K lobbying investment represents 4-8% of revenue—too high for most small businesses to justify.</p>
                    <p class="text-xs text-red-700 italic">Alternative: Join trade association with lobbying coverage, coordinate grassroots advocacy through customers/employees, or accept that you're too small to fight at the Capitol.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="flex items-start gap-4 bg-orange-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                  <div class="flex-shrink-0 text-2xl font-bold text-orange-700">$2-10M</div>
                  <div class="flex-1">
                    <p class="font-semibold text-orange-900 mb-1">Selective Lobbying in Crisis</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-orange-800 mb-2">You can justify lobbying when specific threats emerge, but ongoing year-round representation is probably beyond budget. Focus on defensive issues with clear ROI.</p>
                    <p class="text-xs text-orange-700 italic">Strategy: Hire reactively or in crisis mode when specific bills threaten you. Use trade associations for ongoing monitoring. Budget 1-2% of revenue for lobbying when needed.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="flex items-start gap-4 bg-yellow-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                  <div class="flex-shrink-0 text-2xl font-bold text-yellow-700">$10-50M</div>
                  <div class="flex-1">
                    <p class="font-semibold text-yellow-900 mb-1">Proactive Lobbying Makes Sense</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-yellow-800 mb-2">At this scale, $100K lobbying investment represents 0.2-1% of revenue. You can afford proactive engagement (6-12 months ahead) on specific issues affecting your growth.</p>
                    <p class="text-xs text-yellow-700 italic">Strategy: Hire when you identify specific legislative opportunities or threats. Consider 6-12 month engagements rather than year-round retainers unless regulatory exposure is constant.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="flex items-start gap-4 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                  <div class="flex-shrink-0 text-2xl font-bold text-green-700">$50M+</div>
                  <div class="flex-1">
                    <p class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-1">Strategic Lobbying as Insurance</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-green-800 mb-2">At this revenue, lobbying costs 0.1-0.3% of revenue. You should maintain ongoing Austin representation as strategic insurance, positioning proactively rather than responding to crises.</p>
                    <p class="text-xs text-green-700 italic">Strategy: Year-round retainer or biennial engagement (lower interim rate, higher session rate). Strategic positioning 18+ months ahead. Lobbying becomes core part of government relations function.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="not-prose my-8 space-y-6">
            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-blue-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-3">The Risk Exposure Calculation</h3>
              <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-4">
                Sometimes revenue doesn't tell the full story. Calculate risk exposure to determine if lobbying makes sense at any revenue level:
              </p>
              <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-4 mb-4">
                <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-3">Formula: Risk Exposure = (Probability of harmful legislation × Financial impact) - Lobbying cost</p>
                <div class="space-y-3">
                  <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-blue-200 p-3">
                    <p class="text-xs text-blue-900 mb-1"><strong>Example 1: $5M revenue company, $8M compliance cost threat</strong></p>
                    <p class="text-xs text-blue-800 mb-0">Even if lobbying only has 30% success probability, expected value is $2.4M (30% × $8M) minus $100K lobbying cost = $2.3M net benefit. Do it.</p>
                  </div>
                  <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-blue-200 p-3">
                    <p class="text-xs text-blue-900 mb-1"><strong>Example 2: $3M revenue company, $500K compliance impact</strong></p>
                    <p class="text-xs text-blue-800 mb-0">Even at 50% success probability, expected value is $250K (50% × $500K) minus $100K lobbying cost = $150K net benefit. Marginal—probably not worth it unless success probability is higher.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p class="text-sm text-blue-800 italic">
                When the risk exposure math clearly favors lobbying, revenue size becomes less relevant. A $2M company facing $10M threat should hire a lobbyist. A $50M company facing $200K compliance cost probably shouldn't.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-purple-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-3">Multi-Business Coalitions: Shared Cost Approach</h3>
              <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-4">
                If individual company budgets can't support lobbying, but five similar businesses face the same issue, sharing a lobbyist makes economic sense.
              </p>
              <div class="bg-purple-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                <p class="text-sm text-purple-900 mb-2">
                  <strong>Coalition structure:</strong> Five companies each pay $20K for session engagement ($100K total). Your lobbyist represents the coalition's unified position on shared issues.
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm text-purple-800 mb-0">
                  <strong>When this works:</strong> When interests are truly aligned and no internal disagreements exist. When it fails: coalition members have competing priorities and the lobbyist can't advocate effectively because members contradict each other.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Making the Decision -->
      <section id="decision-framework" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
        <div class="bg-green-50 border-l-4 border-green-500 rounded-r-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">Making the Timing Decision: A Framework</h2>
          <p class="text-green-700 font-medium">Five questions that determine when you should act</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
          <p>
            You've read about warning signals, cost multipliers, timing windows, and budget reality. Now you need to decide: do you hire now, hire later, or not hire at all? Work through these five questions to reach clarity.
          </p>

          <div class="not-prose my-8">
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border-2 border-green-500 overflow-hidden">
              <div class="bg-gradient-to-r from-green-500 to-green-600 p-4">
                <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-0">The Five-Question Decision Framework</h3>
              </div>

              <div class="p-6 space-y-6">
                <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                  <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-10 h-10 bg-green-500 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-bold">1</div>
                  <div class="flex-1">
                    <p class="font-bold mb-2">What specific threat or opportunity requires lobbying?</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">
                      Force yourself to articulate the specific issue. "We need a lobbyist" isn't specific enough. "HB 2847 threatens to ban our product" or "We want to position for $15M in state contracts" is specific.
                    </p>
                    <div class="bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-3">
                      <p class="text-xs text-green-900"><strong>Decision point:</strong> If you can't articulate a specific issue worth 5-10x your lobbying investment, don't hire yet. Wait until you have clear objectives.</p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                  <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-10 h-10 bg-green-500 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-bold">2</div>
                  <div class="flex-1">
                    <p class="font-bold mb-2">How much time do we have before action becomes necessary?</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">
                      Look at interim committee schedules, pre-filing activity, session timing, and agency rulemaking calendars. Are you 18 months ahead, 6 months ahead, or already in crisis mode?
                    </p>
                    <div class="bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-3">
                      <p class="text-xs text-green-900"><strong>Decision point:</strong> Map your issue to one of the four timing windows (strategic, proactive, reactive, crisis). That determines both cost and optimal engagement strategy.</p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                  <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-10 h-10 bg-green-500 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-bold">3</div>
                  <div class="flex-1">
                    <p class="font-bold mb-2">Can we accomplish this without a professional lobbyist?</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">
                      Is trade association coverage sufficient? Can you handle it with direct legislator contact? Will grassroots advocacy work? Or do you genuinely need professional Capitol relationships and strategic expertise?
                    </p>
                    <div class="bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-3">
                      <p class="text-xs text-green-900"><strong>Decision point:</strong> If alternative approaches have reasonable success probability and cost less, try them first. But don't fool yourself—hoping your State Rep's office returns your emails isn't a strategy.</p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                  <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-10 h-10 bg-green-500 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-bold">4</div>
                  <div class="flex-1">
                    <p class="font-bold mb-2">What's the expected ROI at various success probabilities?</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">
                      Run the math: If lobbying costs $100K and success saves $5M with 40% probability, expected value is $2M (40% × $5M) minus $100K cost = $1.9M positive. If it's $100K cost for $300K benefit at 30% probability, expected value is $90K minus $100K = negative $10K. Don't do it.
                    </p>
                    <div class="bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-3">
                      <p class="text-xs text-green-900"><strong>Decision point:</strong> If expected value is positive at reasonable success probabilities, the investment makes sense. If you need 80%+ success rates to break even, you're gambling—probably not worth it.</p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                  <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-10 h-10 bg-green-500 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-bold">5</div>
                  <div class="flex-1">
                    <p class="font-bold mb-2">Can we sustain the financial commitment through completion?</p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">
                      Lobbying engagements typically last 6-24 months. If your budget only covers 3 months and then you have to bail, you've wasted money and burned relationships. Be honest about sustained financial commitment.
                    </p>
                    <div class="bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-3">
                      <p class="text-xs text-green-900"><strong>Decision point:</strong> Don't start if you can't finish. Lobbyists who get stiffed mid-engagement won't take your calls next session when you need them. If budget is uncertain, wait until you have secured funding.</p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="not-prose bg-texas-blue-50 border-l-4 border-texas-blue-500 rounded-r-lg p-6 my-8">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-2">The Gut Check Question</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-texas-blue-900 mb-3">
              After working through the framework, ask yourself this: "If we don't hire a lobbyist and this issue goes badly, will I regret not having professional representation?"
            </p>
            <p class="text-sm text-texas-blue-900 mb-0">
              If the answer is "yes, I'd regret it deeply," hire the lobbyist. If the answer is "we'll be fine either way," you probably don't need one. Trust your gut after you've done the analysis.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Conclusion -->
