        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-texas-blue-50 to-texas-blue-100 rounded-2xl p-8 lg:p-12">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">Timing Determines Success More Than Money</h2>

          <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none mb-8">
            <p>
              The difference between businesses that win at the Capitol and those that waste money comes down to timing. Not how much they spend—though that matters. Not which lobbyist they hire—though that matters too. But when they engage relative to when action becomes necessary.
            </p>

            <p>
              Strategic clients hire 18+ months ahead, positioning before issues become problems. Proactive clients hire 6-12 months out, early enough to shape outcomes. Reactive clients hire last-minute and hope for the best. Crisis clients pay premium prices for low-probability saves.
            </p>

            <p>
              The pattern is predictable: businesses that wait until they're desperate pay more and get less. Businesses that engage early spend strategically and multiply returns. The six-month timing difference determines whether you're shaping the agenda or responding to decisions already made by competitors who showed up first.
            </p>

            <p>
              If you recognize warning signals in this guide, don't rationalize waiting. Every month you delay moves you one window closer to crisis pricing and lower success rates. The optimal time to hire a lobbyist is before you desperately need one—when you have time to build relationships, position strategically, and shape outcomes rather than beg for mercy.
            </p>
